Also, this album to me was about a man who was still guarding himself from having to talk about the very public struggles he’s had to overcome in the past 5 years. From the obvious desire to not talk about how his past 5 years have been, to the low-key flows and moody vocals, to even the distortion effects he so often uses on this LP to masks and hide what he’s saying. I think it’s an incredibly subtle and really interesting theme, and I’m not sure if he consciously decided to put that at the forefront, but it’s really what wraps up the album for me. The sounds of a man who’s overcome but is still too wary to let you see the scars just yet.

So I will say this, originally I would have agreed with almost everything he said on first listen. The singles didn't do to much for me either and the whole first listen I was left wanting so much more.. I left the album for a day and came back. I started to enjoy it slightly more. By the 3rd listen I was picking out some substance. And by the 4th and 5th listen I was thoroughly enjoying the album. Once I got over the initial disappointment, there was alot to enjoy on this album. I could leave it on rotation and not have to skip a single song. Everything just starts to blend together in a very smooth and relaxed way that starts making sense. His other 2 albums have a few jarring tracks on them and some instrumentals and voice inflections that you either love or hate. But this album really just floats in the back of your brain as you keep picking up hints of internal or problematic issues of the world, however it's almost left up to your interpretation, like on the title track "thib". If you really enjoyed his last 2 albums but are feeling let down by this one, I would suggest leaving it on repeat and just let it ride, when your in the car, at home or playing games. I thought it was a downside at first, with him sort of blending into the tracks, however now it starts to make more sense.

Say what you will about this review, but Isaiah’s response to Fantano on Twitter is just not it. Isaiah has a right to disagree with Fantano’s opinion, and he has a right to be very upset about it, but to completely discredit Fantano as a music reviewer is silly. Saying things like “he’s just doing it for views” and “he’s too white to understand” is such an immature viewpoint. Like, he’s clearly not doing anything for views. For one, Fantano reviews everything, from huge artists to underground artists that people have never heard of, it has nothing to do with views. Also, a lot of people want to know what he has to say, so there’s a demand. Trying to discredit certain groups of people from critiquing art is also another terrible thing. So, I’m black, and because I’m not white/Italian, I’m not allowed to critique Renaissance art? The moment you create art for anyone to see, everyone who sees/listens/experiences that art has a right to comment on it. Fantano is not reviewing the black experience or black lives, he’s reviewing the MUSIC, and he didn’t like the music. It’s such a silly thing to bring race into this conversation when his review has nothing to do with race. He’s stated many times that he isn’t black and can never comment on black experiences sung/rapped about in music, so he sticks to commenting solely on the music. I love Isaiah Rashad, and all of TDE, but I’m super disappointed in their responses to Fantano and I hope Fantano is well and doesn’t feel bad. Isaiah needs to understand that this isn’t a personal attack and that Fantano only wants him to succeed. Whenever somebody critiques your work, you should try to take in and understand the criticism, and, hopefully, use it to try to improve your later work. And if you feel really hurt by a review, either keep your thoughts to yourself, or try to be a bit more mature and reasonable when saying things publicly.
